⚡ LEVEL 4: Hyperdrive (Warp Speed)
You are entering the most dangerous quadrant of the financial universe. Derivatives are financial contracts whose value is derived from an underlying asset. They do not represent ownership — they represent agreements and obligations. The global derivatives market dwarfs the stock market in size. 97% of retail traders who enter the Indian F&O segment lose money. This level explains why — and how the 3% survive.

4.1 Afterburners (Leverage and Margin)
Leverage allows you to control a position far larger than your actual capital.

Example:
₹1,00,000 of your own capital + 5x leverage = ₹5,00,000 position size.
If position gains 2%: You made ₹10,000. That is a 10% return on your capital.
If position loses 2%: You lost ₹10,000. A 10% loss on your capital.
If position loses 20%: Your entire ₹1,00,000 capital is gone. Complete account destruction.

Leverage amplifies BOTH wins and losses with perfect symmetry. This is why it kills most traders.

Margin Call and Liquidation:
If your losses eat through your capital below a minimum threshold, your broker issues a Margin Call — a demand for more funds immediately.
If you do not respond, the broker force-closes your position at whatever the current market price is. This locks in the loss permanently.

4.2 Space Contracts (Futures)
A Futures contract is a legally binding OBLIGATION to buy or sell a specific quantity of an asset at a pre-agreed price on a specific expiry date.

Unlike stocks, you cannot simply "hold" a futures position indefinitely. You must either close it before expiry or allow settlement.

Indian Futures Mechanics:
Lot Size: Futures trade in standardized blocks. NIFTY futures = 25 units per contract. One contract is worth roughly ₹5,00,000+.
Expiry: Last Thursday of every month. Three active contracts always: Near-month, Next-month, Far-month.
Mark-to-Market (MTM) Settlement: Your profit or loss is calculated and settled in CASH every single day at 3:30 PM. You gain or lose money daily, not just at expiry.
Rollover: To hold a position beyond expiry, you close the current contract and simultaneously open the next month's contract.

4.3 Strategic Shields (Options Mechanics)
An Options contract gives the BUYER the RIGHT — but not the OBLIGATION — to buy or sell an asset at a specific price before a specific date.
The buyer pays a PREMIUM upfront. Maximum loss for the buyer = the premium paid.

Call Options (CE):
Right to BUY the underlying at the Strike Price.
Buy a Call when you believe the price will RISE.
Example: NIFTY at 22,000. You buy the 22,500 CE for ₹150 premium. NIFTY rallies to 23,000. Your option is now worth ₹500. Profit: ₹350 per unit × 25 = ₹8,750.
If NIFTY falls: Your option expires worthless. Maximum loss: ₹150 × 25 = ₹3,750 only.

Put Options (PE):
Right to SELL the underlying at the Strike Price.
Buy a Put when you believe the price will FALL — or to protect a portfolio you already hold.
Portfolio Insurance: Hold ₹10 Lakh of stocks? Buy Put options to cap your losses in a crash. Exactly like buying insurance.

Options Seller (Writer):
The seller receives the premium and takes on theoretically unlimited risk.
Sellers profit when the option expires worthless — and most options do expire worthless.
Selling options is statistically better odds — but each loss can be enormous without strict hedging.

4.4 The Greeks (Option Sensitivity Controls)
Delta: How much the option price moves for every ₹1 move in the underlying.
Deep ITM options: Delta near 1.0. OTM options: Delta near 0.
Theta (Time Decay): Options lose value every single day as expiry approaches. This rate ACCELERATES in the final week.
Theta is the enemy of option buyers. Theta is the friend — and passive income source — of option sellers.
Vega: How much the option price changes per 1% move in Implied Volatility (IV).
High IV = Expensive options. Low IV = Cheap options. India VIX measures this.
Strategy: Buy options when VIX is low. Sell options when VIX is high.
Gamma: Rate of change of Delta. Extremely high near expiry for ATM options — position becomes hypersensitive.

